We solve this using two arrays "in" and "out" array.
1. The "in" array stores the longest path **starting** at a given node where all nodes have different adjacent labels.
2. The "out" array stores the longest path **ending** at a given node where all nodes have different adjacent labels.

The "in" is used to count the path below the current node considering the current node as well whereas the  "out" array calculates the upper path from the current node.
The "out" array is calculated using the approach that the lower node can go either in the direction ***( child -> parent -> parent of parent )*** or ***( child -> parent -> other child with the max length)*** . Hence if the current node chain has the max length then consider the second max chain.
```
class Solution {
    //canVisit[i] contains the nodes that can be visited from node i
    private List<Integer>[] canVisit;
    //in[i] stores the longest path starting at node i where all nodes have different labels
    private int[] in;
    //out[i] stores the longest path ending at node i where all nodes have different labels
    private int[] out;
    //labels[i] is the label of node i
    private char[] labels;

    public int longestPath(int[] parent, String s) 
    {
        int n = parent.length;

        //initialize canVisit
        canVisit = new ArrayList[n];
        for(int i=0; i<n; i++)
            canVisit[i] = new ArrayList<>();

        //populate canVisit
        for(int i=1; i<n; i++)
        {
            canVisit[parent[i]].add(i); //adding child nodes to the parent's ArrayList
        }

        //initialize in, out and labels
        in = new int[n];
        out = new int[n];
        labels = s.toCharArray();

        //populate in array
        inside(0);

        //populate out array
        outside(0);

        //find the maximum length path
        int max = -1;
        for(int i=0; i<n; i++)
        {
            max = Math.max(max, in[i]+out[i]);
        }
        return max;

    }
    //helper function to populate in array
    void inside(int node)
    {
        in[node] = 1; //length of path starting from a node is at least 1
        for(int i : canVisit[node])
        { 
            inside(i);
            //if the child node has a different label than the current node, update the max length of path
            if(labels[i] != labels[node]) in[node] = Math.max(in[node],in[i]+1);
        }
    }

    //helper function to populate out array
    void outside(int node)
    {
        //mx stores the longest path from the children of the current node
        //mx2 stores the second longest path from the children of the current node
        int mx=0, mx2=0;
        //find the two longest path from the children of the current node
        for(int child: canVisit[node])
        {
            //if the child has the same label as current node, skip it
            if(labels[child] == labels[node]) continue; 

            //update mx and mx2
            if( in[child]+1 >= mx) 
            {
                mx2 = mx ; 
                mx = in[child] + 1;
            }
            else if( in[child]+1 >= mx2) 
            {
                mx2 = in[child]+1;
            }
        }
        //update out array for each child
        for(int child : canVisit[node])
        {
            //if the child has a different label than the current node
            if(labels[child] != labels[node])
            {
                out[child] = out[node] + 1;
                //if the current child is not the one with the longest path
                if(mx != in[child] + 1) 
                    out[child] = Math.max(mx, out[child]);
                else 
                    out[child] = Math.max(out[child], mx2);
            }
            //recursively call outside function for each child
            outside(child);
        }
    }
}
```
