# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
For there to be a path, there are three options for the nodes in the path; it can be an end node, come up from one of the branches and go down the other, or go up to the parent. The end nodes are built in, as there are no children to do the pathing, and an end that is the parent is also handled by sending up to the parent. 

Since each node only has one parent, there can only be one node where the path is on two branches. This means we can check the most optimal path at each node to find this path. 

Otherwise, we will always want to use the best path at each node, as the previous nodes don't affect the rest of the path, as the children will check against the parent and not the ancestors beyond the parent. 

If they share a tag, we can check that node, but don't include it in the path.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
I use a shared variable to store the best path. I use DFS in order to find the best and second path of each node that contain that node. I also try to check nodes that match the parent, but don't record the path as the best path as it can't be used with the parent node. However, the overall best path found will be recorded. 
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$O(n)$ time complexity, as it is a DFS on a tree and at each step is $O(1)$ as it is just a comparison. Thus, the total time complexity is $O(n)$.
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$O(n)$ as there are a total of n nodes, so there is $O(n)$ sized array, and total size of the vectors is $O(n)$ as every node can only have one parent, so it appears once in the vectors. The recursion stack is also $O(n)$.   
