# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Variation of standard tree problem of finding the max_path between any two nodes, But this one has some additional constraints
    - the parent and child must have different alphabets.
    - And in this one parent can have more than two child as given in question

https://leetcode.com/problems/binary-tree-maximum-path-sum/
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
So if it was a tree and no constraints were given ie. we just have to find the max path length between any two nodes so, we would have recursively built the dfs function and while returning we would have have returned 1+max(left,right) and updated our answer as ans=max(ans,left+right+1).
where left is the maximum path length in the left subtree and right is the max path length in the right subtree.

---


Now coming to this question, we have more than two childs, but what we have to care about is the two of them which gives us the maximum path lengths among all of them ( so they would be considered as our left and right as discussed in previous analogy )

But before considering the child of any node in our answer we have check for one another thing that the **s[child] != s[curr_node]**

For implementation, refer comments in code given below.


# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n)$$

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
Virtual recursion space : $$O(h+n)$$ where h = height of tree. and n=number of nodes in the graph.

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int dfs(int curr_node,int parent,vector<vector<int>>&adj,string &s,int &ans) {
        // first maximum and second maximum length
        int fmax=0,smax=0;  

        // traversing the childs of current node
        for(auto child:adj[curr_node]) { 

        /* check so that we do not stuck in an infinite recursive
loop, no need to make a visited array as it a tree where every
node has only one parent */

            if(child==parent) continue;

            //recursively calling dfs for getting max path length
            // from it's childs subtree and storing it in temp

            int temp=dfs(child,curr_node,adj,s,ans); 

            //adjacent nodes must not have same character
            if(s[child]!=s[curr_node]) {
                if(temp>=fmax) {
                    smax=fmax;
                    fmax=temp;
                }else if(temp>=smax) smax=temp;
            }
        }


    /* considering the path from  
          curr_node
         /  / | \ \
        /          \
       /          smax
     fmax
    */
        ans=max(ans,1+fmax+smax);

    // while returning we must include the curr_node with any of it's 
    //child, but we want max_path so we will include the one which
    //gives the maximum path.
        return 1+fmax;

    }
    int longestPath(vector<int>& par, string s) {
        int n=par.size(),ans=0;

//making adjacency list for graph
        vector<vector<int>>adj(n); 
        for(int i=1;i<n;i++) {  // start from 1 here as 0th node
                                // does not have any parent
            adj[par[i]].emplace_back(i);
            adj[i].emplace_back(par[i]);
        }
        dfs(0,-1,adj,s,ans);
        return ans;
    }
};
```

